.H 1 "Controlling Access to CDS Names"
.P
This chapter presents information on the following CDS authorization topics:
.ML
.LI
Overview of DCE authorization for CDS
.LI
DCE authorization components supported by CDS 
.LI
DCE permissions supported by CDS 
.LI
Controlling access to CDS clerk and server management operations
.LI
Control program commands and required permissions
.LI
Editing ACLs on CDS names 
.LI
How CDS servers gain access to the namespace
.LI
Setting up access control in a new namespace
.LE
.H 2 "Overview of DCE Authorization for CDS"
.P
.iX "-[" "ACLs" "for local names (CDS)"
.iX "-[" "local" "names" "access control"
CDS authorization allows you to control user access to the
following CDS components:
.ML
.LI
Names that are stored in the namespace, including clearinghouses, directories,
object entries, soft links, and child pointers
.LI
Execution of privileged CDS clerk and server commands
.LE
.P
.iX "-: ACL" "access control list"
You control access to a name in the namespace by creating an 
ACL.  An ACL contains individual
ACL entries that specify the permissions you grant a user (principal)
to the name with which the ACL is associated.  The ACL entries that you
create determine collectively which principals can use the name and what
management operations they are allowed to perform on it.
.P
CDS ACL management software, incorporated into all CDS clerks and servers,
performs access checking for incoming CDS requests.  When a principal
requests an operation on a CDS name, ACL management
software on a server that stores the name
examines the ACL entries associated with the name.  The software then
grants or denies the operation, based on the permissions
granted to the requesting principal in the ACL entries.  Similarly, when
a principal requests a privileged operation on a CDS clerk
or server, ACL management software on that system examines the 
ACL entries that are 
associated with the principal name that represents the clerk or server.  The
software then grants or denies the operation, based on the permissions
granted to the requesting principal in the ACL entries.
.P
The DCE control program (\*Ldcecp\*O) provides commands that
add, modify, copy, delete, and display ACLs that are associated with CDS
names, clerks, and servers.  See the \*(Ar for detailed information on
the commands.  The remainder of this chapter describes DCE authorization as
it applies specifically to CDS.  Before you try to create or modify
permissions to CDS names, clerks, or servers, read Part 6 of this guide
...\" Security part
for complete information on the DCE authorization mechanism.
.H 2 "ACL Types Supported by CDS"
.iX "ACLs" "types"
CDS supports the following DCE ACL types:
.ML
.LI
.iX "Object ACL"
Object ACL\(emYou can use the Object ACL type to grant permissions
to any CDS name (that is, object entries, soft links, child pointers,
clearinghouses, and directories), as well as to CDS clerks and servers.  When
associated with a CDS directory, the permissions you grant with
the Object ACL type apply only to the directory itself, not to the
directory's contents or to any child directories.
.LI
.iX "Initial Object ACL"
Initial Object Creation ACL\(emThe Initial Object Creation ACL type
applies only to CDS directory names.
Use this ACL type to grant permissions specifically to a
directory's future contents, including soft links, application-defined object
entries, child pointers, and clearinghouse object entries.  The permissions
you grant by using the Initial Object Creation ACL type
apply only to the future contents of the directory,
not to the directory itself.
The permissions
are inherited only by names that are created in the
directory \*Eafter\*O you create the ACL entry;
permissions are not propagated to names that already exist in the directory.
.P
To edit an Initial Object Creation ACL, you use the
\%\*L-io\*O option of the \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lacl modify\*O command.
.LI
.iX "Initial Container ACL"
Initial Container Creation ACL\(emThe Initial Container Creation ACL
type applies only to CDS directory names.  Use this ACL type to grant
permissions to a directory that automatically propagate (the default) 
to all child directories that you may later
create under that directory.  The permissions you grant by using the
Initial Container Creation ACL type
are inherited only by the child directories that you create
\*Eafter\*O you create the ACL entry; permissions are not propagated to child
directories that already exist.
.P
To edit an Initial Container Creation ACL, you use the
\%\*L-ic\*O option of the \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lacl modify\*O command.
.LE
.H 2 "How Permissions Propagate to CDS Directories and Their Contents"
.P
.iX "-[" "directories" "access control (CDS)"
.iX "permissions" "propagation"
By creating all three ACL types
(Object ACL, Initial Object Creation ACL, and Initial Container Creation
ACL)
for a directory, you can grant access not only to the
directory itself but also to
the directory's future contents and all child directories (and their
contents) that may later be created.
.nS "note"
Permissions do not propagate from parent cells to child cells.  You
must set permissions for each child cell individually.
.nE
.P
For example, suppose you just created a new directory named
\*L/.:/sales\*O.
If you create an ACL entry of the Object ACL type that grants user
\*LSmith\*O read permission to the \*L/.:/sales\*O
directory, \*LSmith\*O can do the following:
.ML
.LI
Read the attributes associated with the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Display the names stored in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LE
.P
If you create a second ACL entry of the
Initial Object Creation ACL type that grants user
\*LSmith\*O read permission to the \*L/.:/sales\*O
directory, \*LSmith\*O can do the following:
.ML
.LI
Read the attributes associated with the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Display the names stored in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Read the attributes associated with all the names that you may later create
in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory, unless prohibited by explicit ACL
modification after their creation
.LE
.P
If you create a third ACL entry of the  
Initial Container Creation ACL type that
also grants user \*LSmith\*O read permission to the \*L/.:/sales\*O
directory, \*LSmith\*O can do the following:
.ML
.LI
Read the attributes associated with the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Display the names stored in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Read the attributes associated with all the names that you may later create
in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LI
Perform all of the three preceding operations on all child
directories that may later be created under the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory
.LE
.P
(See Part 6 of this guide 
...\" Security part
for complete information on default ACLs.) 
.iX "-]" "directories" "access control (CDS)" 
.H 2 "ACL Entry Types Used for Principals"
.iX "-[" "ACLs" "entry types" 
You use ACL entry types to specify the category of principal for which the
ACL entry is created.  These ACL entry types are described in Table 16-1.
.P
.TB "ACL Entry Types Used for CDS Principals"
.TS H
center,allbox,tab(@);
lB | lB
lB | lw(3.25i).
Entry Type@Purpose
_
.TH
user@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an individual principal whose credentials were
authenticated within the local cell.
T}
group@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an authorization group whose members have been
authenticated within the local cell.
T}
other_obj@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for authenticated principals in the local cell
who are not individual users named by an ACL entry of the type \*Luser\*O
or members of a group named by an ACL entry of the type or \*Lgroup\*O.
T}
foreign_user@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an authenticated principal in a foreign cell.
T}
foreign_group@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an authorization group whose members were
authenticated in a foreign cell.
T}
foreign_other@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for authenticated principals in a foreign cell who
are not individual users named by an ACL entry of the type \*Lforeign_user\*O
or members of a group named by an ACL entry of the type \*Lforeign_group\*O.
T}
any_other@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an authenticated principal who 
is not otherwise covered by any of the preceding ACL entry types.
T}
mask_obj@T{
Specifies an ACL entry containing a mask that is substituted for the
permissions of any principals, whose credentials are either authenticated
or unauthenticated.
T}
unauthenticated@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for principals who cannot pass authentication
procedures.
T}
user_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for an
authenticated principal in the local cell.
T}
group_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for the authenticated
principals who are members of an authorization group in the local cell.
T}
other_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for authenticated
principals in the local cell who are not individual users named by an
ACL entry of the type \*Luser_delegate\*O or who are not members of a group
named by an ACL entry of the type \*Lgroup_delegate\*O.
T}
foreign_user_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for an authenticated
principal in a foreign cell.
T}
foreign_group_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for the members of
an authorization group in a foreign cell.
T}
foreign_other_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for authenticated
principals in a foreign cell who are not individual users named by an
ACL entry of the type \*Lforeign_user_delegate\*O or members of a group
named by an ACL entry of the type \*Lforeign_group_delegate\*O.
T}
any_other_delegate@T{
Specifies an ACL entry for an intermediary that acts for authenticated
principals in the local cell or in a foreign cell who are not named by
an ACL entry of any other type for intermediaries of authenticated
principals or groups.
T}
.TE
.iX "-]" "ACLs" "entry types"
.H 2 "DCE Permissions Supported by CDS"
.P
.iX "-[" "permissions" "CDS objects"
CDS supports the following DCE permissions:
read (\*Lr\*O),
write (\*Lw\*O), 
insert (\*Li\*O),
delete (\*Ld\*O),
test (\*Lt\*O),
control (\*Lc\*O), and
administer (\*La\*O).
Each permission has a slightly different meaning, depending on the kind of
CDS name with which it is associated.  In general, the permissions are
defined as follows:
.ML
.LI
Read Permission\(emAllows a principal to look up a name and view the
attribute values that are associated with it.
.LI
Write Permission\(emAllows a principal to change the modifiable
attributes that are associated with a name, except its ACLs. 
.LI
Insert Permission\(emAllows a principal to create 
new names in a directory (for use with directory entries only). 
.LI
Delete Permission\(emAllows a principal to delete a name from the
namespace.
.LI
Test Permission\(emAllows a principal to test whether an attribute
of a name has a particular value without being able to actually see any of
the values; that is, without having read permission to the name.
.P
Test permission provides application programs with
a more efficient way to verify a
CDS attribute value.  Rather than reading an entire set of values, an
application can test for the presence of a particular value.
...\" 
...\" 
...\" 
.LI
Control Permission\(emAllows a principal to modify the ACL entries
that are associated with a name. 
(Note that read permission is also necessary
for modifying a CDS entry's ACLs; otherwise, \*Ldcecp\*O and \*Lacl_edit\*O
will not be able to bind to the entry.)  Control permission is automatically
granted to the creator of a CDS entry.
...\" 
...\" 
...\" 
.LI
Administer Permission\(emAllows a principal 
to issue CDS commands that control the replication of
directories.  Administer permission is
for use with directory entries only.
.LE
.P
A principal needs some permission to a name before it can try to perform
management operations on the name.  Otherwise, CDS does not recognize
the name when the principal tries the management operation and returns
an error stating that the name does not exist.  If the principal has some
permissions, but not those required to perform the operation, CDS
returns an error explaining that the principal had insufficient rights
to perform the operation.
.P
The creator of a name is automatically granted all permissions 
that are appropriate for the type of name that is created. 
For example, a principal that is creating an object
entry is granted read, write, delete, test, and control permissions to
the object entry.  A principal that is creating a directory is granted read,
write, insert, delete, test, control, and administer permissions to
the directory.
.nS "note"
Unlike the security mechanisms that are enforced by most other file
systems, CDS does not require a principal to have access to all
intermediate elements in the pathname (full name) of a name in order to
perform an operation on the name.  For example, consider an object entry 
\*Lobject1\*O stored in the \*L/.:/sales\*O directory.  In CDS, you can grant
a principal access to the
object entry \*L/.:/sales/object1\*O without necessarily granting
the principal access to either the
\*L/.:/sales\*O directory or the cell root directory (\*L/.:\*O).
.nE
.iX "-]" "permissions" "CDS objects"
.H 2 "Controlling Access to CDS Clerk and Server Management Operations"
.iX "-[" "CDS" "controlling local management operations"
CDS authorization allows you to control the use of CDS commands that
involve local management operations on CDS clerks and servers.  Principal
names for each clerk and server are stored in the security
namespace.  An object entry that contains the binding information for
each clerk and server is stored in the CDS namespace in the
\*L/.:/hosts\*O subdirectory.  Servers are represented as
\*L/.:/hosts/\*O\*Vhostname\*O\*L/cds-server\*O.  Clerks are represented as
\*L/.:/hosts/\*O\*Vhostname\*O\*L/cds-clerk\*O.
.P
.ne 5
Each clerk and server
maintains a separate ACL that
contains entries specifying the principals allowed to perform these
operations.  Unlike the ACLs that are associated 
with names in the namespace, the ACLs that are associated
with clerks and servers exist exclusively to provide local control of the use
of these commands.
.P
Whenever a new clerk or server is initialized, 
an ACL is created on the clerk or server system.
An initial ACL entry is also created, granting the
machine principal and the namespace authorization group
(\*Lsubsys/dce/cds-admin\*O) read, write, and control permissions to the
clerk or server process on that system.  All other principals, both
authenticated and unauthenticated, are granted read permission.
The creation of this ACL entry ensures that, immediately after its
creation, any user logged into the system as the machine principal 
is permitted to execute privileged clerk or server CDS commands.
.nS "note"
Use of the machine principal for this purpose is provided as a
convenience and assumes that the account itself (user name and password) is
already moderately secure.  Namespace administrators may prefer to modify
this scheme and grant permission to particular
clerks and servers on behalf of other individual principals or
authorization groups.
.nE
.P
To edit an ACL that is associated with a CDS clerk or server, you
use the \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lacl modify\*O command with the
\%\*L-change\*O option.  For example, to change the permissions for the user
\*Lmichaels\*O in the ACL that is associated
with the CDS clerk on node \*Lorion\*O, enter the following command:
.iS
\*Cdcecp> \*Lacl modify /.:/hosts/orion/cds-clerk -change {user michaels rw}\*O
\*Cdcecp>
.iE
.P
Keep in mind that clerks and servers are also represented by
entries in the namespace.  To edit an ACL that is
associated with the namespace entry for a CDS clerk or server,
you must include the \%\*L-entry\*O option, as well as the 
\%\*L-change\*O option,
in the \*Lacl modify\*O command line.  For detailed instructions on how
to modify an ACL on the CDS entry for a DCE resource, see Section 16.8.
.iX "-]" "CDS" "controlling local management operations"
.H 2 "Control Program Commands and Required Permissions"
.P
.iX "-[" "\*Ldcecp\*O commands" "required permissions"
.iX "-[" "permissions" "\*Ldcecp\*O for CDS"
Table 16-2 lists all the \*Ldcecp\*O commands that operate on CDS
objects and the permissions that a principal must have to
execute the commands.
