.H 2 "Editing ACLs on CDS Names"
.P
...\" .iX "\*Ldcecp\*O command"
.iX "commands" "\*Ldcecp\*O"
.iX "-[" "CDS" "servers" "permissions"
To edit an ACL that is associated with an entry in the CDS namespace
for a child directory, clearinghouse, soft link, or some other CDS object,
specify the \%\*L-entry\*O option to any \*Ldcecp\*O \*Lacl\*O
command.  The \%\*L-entry\*O option is especially useful in case of an ambiguous
pathname.  In some cases, a pathname can resolve to a leaf object in the
DCE Directory Service \*Eand\*O to an object in some other 
DCE component that supports ACLs.  In these cases, you must use the 
\%\*L-entry\*O option to edit the leaf object in CDS.  You do not need to
specify this option to edit ACLs that are associated with actual
clearinghouses or directories.  
.P
For example, to edit the permissions in the Object ACL that is associated with
a CDS entry for a clearinghouse named \*L/.:/Paris1_CH\*O, you would enter
the following command:
.iS
\*Cdcecp> \*Lacl modify /.:/Paris1_CH -entry -change {unauthenticated -}
\*Cdcecp> 
.iE
.P
To edit the permissions in the Object ACL that is associated with the
\*L/.:/Paris1_CH\*O clearinghouse itself, you would enter the following
command:
.iS
\*Cdcecp> \*Lacl modify  /.:/Paris1_CH  -change {unauthenticated -}
\*Cdcecp> 
.iE
.P
Another example is the soft link \*L/.../eng_printer\*O.  The target of this 
soft link is \*L/.../boston.com/print_server\*O.  To edit 
the soft link leaf entry that is in the CDS namespace, enter the following
command:
.iS
\*Cdcecp> \*Lacl modify /.../eng_printer -change -entry \\
\*C> \*L{group subsys/dce/cds-admin rwdtc}
\*Cdcecp> 
.iE
.H 2 "How CDS Servers Gain Access to the Namespace"
.iX "-[" "namespace" "access by CDS servers"
CDS servers require permission to the cell
root directory and to lower-level
directories to successfully execute the following CDS commands:
.ML
.LI
\*Lclearinghouse create\*O
.LI
\*Ldirectory create\*O (For directories and replicas)
.LI
\*Ldirectory delete\*O (For directories and replicas)
.LI
\*Ldirectory synchronize\*O
.LE
.P
To automate the process of granting all CDS servers the permissions that
they require, the CDS cell configuration process creates 
an authorization group for CDS servers under the fixed name
\*Lsubsys/dce/cds-servers\*O.  The principal name of the initial server
in the cell is added to this group as part
of the configuration process.  Immediately after the group is created,
the configuration process grants full permissions
(\*Lr\*O, \*Lw\*O, \*Li\*O, \*Ld\*O, \*Lt\*O, \*Lc\*O, \*La\*O)
to the cell root directory of the new namespace on
behalf of the group.  ACL entries of the
Object ACL and Initial Container Creation ACL types
are created by specifying
\*Lsubsys/dce/cds-servers\*O as the principal in each ACL entry.
This ensures that the group has full access to all future directories and
their contents.
.P
Thereafter, whenever a new server is configured in the cell, the
server configuration process automatically adds the principal name of the new
server to the group.  Through this process, all CDS servers in the
cell receive adequate permissions to all directories in the namespace.
.iX "-]" "CDS" "servers" "permissions"
.iX "-]" "namespace" "access by CDS servers"
.iX "-]" "permissions" "\*Ldcecp\*O for CDS"
.iX "-]" "\*Ldcecp\*O commands" "required permissions"
.H 2 "Setting Up Access Control in a New Namespace"
.iX "-[" "namespace" "access control"
You should plan a consistent access
control policy and be ready to implement the policy as soon as you 
configure your first CDS server and
\*Ebefore\*O you create or populate any new directories.  Among the tasks
you can perform are the following:
.ML
.LI
Adding members to the namespace authorization group
.LI
Creating additional authorization groups
.LI
Establishing maximum permissions for unauthenticated principals
.LE 
.H 3 "Adding Members to the Namespace Authorization Group"
.iX "-[" "authorization groups" "adding members"
To facilitate managing and troubleshooting your namespace,
the cell configuration process creates a namespace authorization
group under the fixed name \*Lsubsys/dce/cds-admin\*O. 
The configuration process then grants the group full access to the cell
root directory.  This access propagates to the entire namespace as it
evolves.
.P
Immediately after its creation, the authorization
group contains only the name that the initial namespace
administrator specified during the cell configuration process.  You can use the
\*Ldcecp\*O \*Lgroup add\*O command to add the principal names of
other individuals in your organization who you want to administer and
troubleshoot the namespace.
Because this group possesses full access to the entire namespace,
its members can intervene, whenever necessary, to solve problems for
namespace users with fewer permissions.  By removing a user's principal name
from the group, the user described by that principal loses
the access assigned to the group.
.P
(See Part 6 of this guide 
...\" Security part
for complete information on how to add and delete group members.)
.iX "-]" "authorization groups" "adding members"
.H 3 "Creating Additional Authorization Groups"
.iX "authorization groups" "creating"
Authorization groups can provide a convenient and flexible
way to control access
to your namespace.  You can combine users according to organization,
work type, security status, and so on, and then grant each group a specific
set of permissions to specific directories or other names in the namespace.
.P
To delegate authority locally, you can create an 
authorization group for each of the functional directories that you plan
to create in your namespace.  For example, you could create an authorization
group named \*Lsubsys/dce/sales-admin\*O and include, as
members, the individuals who are responsible for managing the \*L/.:/sales\*O
directory.  Each local authorization group could have full access to the
contents of the directory for which it is responsible.
.iX "-]" "namespace" "access control"
.H 3 "Establishing Maximum Permissions for Unauthenticated Principals"
.iX "principals" "unauthenticated"
.iX "principals" "permissions"
If you want to apply a namespace-wide set of maximum permissions for all
unauthenticated principals, you should do so immediately \*Eafter\*O you
configure your first CDS server and \*Ebefore\*O you create and populate
any directories below the cell root. 
By creating an unauthenticated ACL
entry and an \*Lany_other\*O entry for the cell root by
using the Object ACL and Initial Container
Creation ACL types, you can take advantage of 
automatic propagation of the unauthenticated
entry to the entire namespace as it evolves.
.iX "-]" "ACLs" "for local names (CDS)"
.iX "-]" "local" "names" "access control"
